### 4. Admin View: Real-Time Dashboard
This is the most critical part. We use Supabase's `subscribe` feature to listen for new rows in the `orders` table.

```tsx
// app/admin/page.tsx
'use client';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { supabase } from '@/lib/supabase';

export default function AdminDashboard() {
  const [orders, setOrders] = useState<any[]>([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Initial Fetch
    fetchOrders();

    // Subscribe to REAL-TIME changes
    const channel = supabase
      .channel('realtime-orders')
      .on('postgres_changes', { 
          event: 'INSERT', 
          schema: 'public', 
          table: 'orders' 
      }, (payload) => {
        setOrders((prev) => [payload.new, ...prev]);
        new Audio('/notification.mp3').play(); // Sound alert for kitchen
      })
      .subscribe();

    return () => { supabase.removeChannel(channel); };
  }, []);

  async function fetchOrders() {
    const { data } = await supabase
      .from('orders')
      .select('*, order_items(quantity, products(name))')
      .order('created_at', { ascending: false });
    setOrders(data || []);
  }

  const updateStatus = async (id: string, status: string) => {
    await supabase.from('orders').update({ status }).eq('id', id);
    fetchOrders(); // Refresh list
  };

  return (
    <div className="p-8 bg-gray-50 min-h-screen">
      <h1 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Kitchen Display System</h1>
      <div className="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        {orders.map((order) => (
          <div key={order.id} className="bg-white p-4 shadow rounded-lg border-l-4 border-orange-500">
            <div className="flex justify-between items-center mb-2">
              <span className="font-bold">Table {order.table_number}</span>
              <span className="text-sm text-gray-500">{new Date(order.created_at).toLocaleTimeString()}</span>
            </div>
            <ul className="mb-4">
              {order.order_items?.map((item: any) => (
                <li key={item.id}>{item.quantity}x {item.products.name}</li>
              ))}
            </ul>
            <div className="flex gap-2">
              <button 
                onClick={() => updateStatus(order.id, 'preparing')}
                className="bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 px-3 py-1 rounded text-sm"
              >
                Cook
              </button>
              <button 
                onClick={() => updateStatus(order.id, 'ready')}
                className="bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-3 py-1 rounded text-sm"
              >
                Done
              </button>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

### Key Technical Decisions Explained

1.  **Supabase Realtime vs. Polling:** I chose Supabase Realtime because it reduces server load and provides a much "snappier" feel for the kitchen staff. Orders pop up instantly without refreshing.
2.  **Relational Data (Postgres):** Unlike NoSQL (Firebase), using Postgres allows us to easily generate reports later (e.g., "What was the most sold item today?"). In NoSQL, this would require complex data duplication.
3.  **Zustand for State:** Cart state doesn't need to persist in a database until the order is finalized. Zustand allows us to share the cart across different components (Menu, Cart Drawer, Checkout) with zero performance overhead.
4.  **Audio Notifications:** In a noisy kitchen, visual cues aren't enough. The `new Audio().play()` trigger on the real-time event is a small but vital "production-ready" detail.

### How to deploy

1.  **Database:** Create a project at [supabase.com](https://supabase.com), run the SQL schema provided above.
2.  **Environment Variables:** Add `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` and `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` to your project.
3.  **Hosting:** Connect your GitHub repo to **Vercel**. It will automatically detect Next.js and deploy.
4.  **Security:** Ensure you enable **RLS (Row Level Security)** in Supabase so that customers can't delete orders or modify prices.

