This is a comprehensive guide to building a production-ready backend for a Recipe App. We will focus on a robust architecture that handles complex relational data (like ingredients and nutritional facts) and supports user-generated variations.

---

### 1. The Technology Stack

I have selected the following stack based on scalability, developer velocity, and data integrity:

*   **Runtime:** **Node.js with TypeScript**. TypeScript is essential for a recipe app to ensure that units of measurement and nutritional values are typed correctly across the system.
*   **Framework:** **NestJS**. While Express is popular, NestJS provides an out-of-the-box architecture (Modules, Controllers, Services) that is more maintainable for production environments.
*   **Database:** **PostgreSQL**. Recipes are highly relational (Ingredients belong to Recipes, Variations belong to Original Recipes). A relational database ensures data integrity via foreign keys and ACID compliance.
*   **ORM:** **Prisma**. Prisma provides a type-safe API for our database, making it much easier to handle nested writes (e.g., creating a recipe + ingredients + instructions in one transaction).
*   **Validation:** **class-validator**. Ensures that incoming API data meets our schema requirements before hitting the logic layer.

---

### 2. Database Schema (Prisma)

The schema is the backbone. We need to handle 1-to-many (Recipe to Ingredients) and 1-to-1 (Recipe to Nutrition) relationships, as well as a self-referential relationship for Variations.

```prisma
// prisma/schema.prisma

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

model User {
  id         String      @id @default(uuid())
  email      String      @unique
  password   String
  recipes    Recipe[]    @relation("UserRecipes")
  variations Variation[]
}

model Recipe {
  id           String        @id @default(uuid())
  title        String
  description  String?
  prepTime     Int           // in minutes
  cookTime     Int           // in minutes
  author       User          @relation("UserRecipes", fields: [authorId], references: [id])
  authorId     String

  ingredients  Ingredient[]
  instructions Instruction[]
  nutrition    Nutrition?    // 1-to-1 relationship

  variations   Variation[]   @relation("OriginalRecipe")
  createdAt    DateTime      @default(now())
  updatedAt    DateTime      @updatedAt
}

model Ingredient {
  id       String @id @default(uuid())
  name     String
  amount   Float
  unit     String // e.g., "grams", "tsp"
  recipeId String
  recipe   Recipe @relation(fields: [recipeId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
}

model Instruction {
  id         String @id @default(uuid())
  stepNumber Int
  text       String
  recipeId   String
  recipe     Recipe @relation(fields: [recipeId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
}

model Nutrition {
  id       String @id @default(uuid())
  calories Float
  protein  Float
  fat      Float
  carbs    Float
  recipeId String @unique
  recipe   Recipe @relation(fields: [recipeId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
}

model Variation {
  id               String @id @default(uuid())
  note             String // What was changed? (e.g., "Used almond milk instead")
  originalRecipe   Recipe @relation("OriginalRecipe", fields: [originalRecipeId], references: [id])
  originalRecipeId String
  author           User   @relation(fields: [authorId], references: [id])
  authorId         String
  createdAt        DateTime @default(now())
}
```

---

### 3. Implementation: The Recipe Service

In a production app, the "Create Recipe" logic is the most complex because it involves multiple tables. Using Prisma, we can perform a **Nested Write**, ensuring that if one part fails (e.g., adding an ingredient), the entire recipe creation is rolled back.

```typescript
// src/recipes/recipes.service.ts

import { Injectable } from '@nestjs/common';
import { PrismaService } from '../prisma/prisma.service';
import { CreateRecipeDto } from './dto/create-recipe.dto';

@Injectable()
export class RecipesService {
  constructor(private prisma: PrismaService) {}

  async create(authorId: string, dto: CreateRecipeDto) {
    return this.prisma.recipe.create({
      data: {
        title: dto.title,
        description: dto.description,
        prepTime: dto.prepTime,
        cookTime: dto.cookTime,
        author: { connect: { id: authorId } },

        // Nested creation of ingredients
        ingredients: {
          create: dto.ingredients.map(ing => ({
            name: ing.name,
            amount: ing.amount,
            unit: ing.unit,
          })),
        },

        // Nested creation of instructions
        instructions: {
          create: dto.instructions.map((inst, index) => ({
            stepNumber: index + 1,
            text: inst.text,
          })),
        },

        // Nested creation of nutritional data
        nutrition: {
          create: {
            calories: dto.nutrition.calories,
            protein: dto.nutrition.protein,
            fat: dto.nutrition.fat,
            carbs: dto.nutrition.carbs,
          },
        },
      },
      include: {
        ingredients: true,
        instructions: true,
        nutrition: true,
      },
    });
  }

  async findOne(id: string) {
    return this.prisma.recipe.findUnique({
      where: { id },
      include: {
        ingredients: true,
        instructions: true,
        nutrition: true,
        variations: {
          include: { author: { select: { email: true } } }
        }
      },
    });
  }
}
```

