### 2. The Backend (Node.js + Prisma)

First, we define our data model. We need to store the expression (e.g., `2 + 2`), the result, and the associated server name.

**`server/prisma/schema.prisma`**
```prisma
datasource db {
  provider = "sqlite"
  url      = "file:./dev.db"
}

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

model Calculation {
  id         Int      @id @default(autoincrement())
  expression String
  result     String
  serverName String   @default("Default-Server")
  createdAt  DateTime @default(now())
}
```

**`server/index.ts` (API Implementation)**
```typescript
import express from 'express';
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';
import cors from 'cors';

const prisma = new PrismaClient();
const app = express();
app.use(cors());
app.use(express.json());

// Get all history
app.get('/api/history', async (req, res) => {
  const history = await prisma.calculation.findMany({
    orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' },
    take: 20
  });
  res.json(history);
});

// Save new calculation
app.post('/api/calculate', async (req, res) => {
  const { expression, result, serverName } = req.body;
  try {
    const saved = await prisma.calculation.create({
      data: { expression, result, serverName }
    });
    res.status(201).json(saved);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "Failed to save calculation" });
  }
});

app.listen(3001, () => console.log('Backend running on http://localhost:3001'));
```

