### 1. The Database Schema (Prisma)

We will store coordinates using a `geography` type in PostgreSQL. This allows us to calculate distances in meters accurately over the earth's curvature.

```prisma
// prisma/schema.prisma

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

model User {
  id        String   @id @default(cuid())
  name      String
  image     String?
  // We store lat/lng as floats for easy access, 
  // but we will query against a spatial index
  lat       Float
  lng       Float
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
}

model Event {
  id          String   @id @default(cuid())
  title       String
  description String
  date        DateTime
  lat         Float
  lng         Float
  address     String
}
```

**Crucial Step:** You must enable PostGIS in your Postgres instance and add a spatial index via a migration:
```sql
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS postgis;
-- Create a spatial index for performance
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS "user_location_idx" ON "User" USING GIST (ST_GeographyFromText('POINT(' || lng || ' ' || lat || ')'));
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS "event_location_idx" ON "Event" USING GIST (ST_GeographyFromText('POINT(' || lng || ' ' || lat || ')'));
```

