This is a sophisticated engineering challenge. To build a production-ready real-time collaborative editor, we must address the "Consistency, Availability, and Partition-tolerance" (CAP) theorem, specifically focusing on how multiple users can edit the same character at the same time without losing data.

### Technical Stack Selection

| Component | Choice | Alternatives | Why? |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Concurrency Logic** | **CRDT (Yjs)** | OT (Operational Transformation) | OT (used by Google Docs) requires a central "truth" server and is notoriously hard to implement. CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types) are mathematically guaranteed to converge, handle offline work better, and are easier to scale. |
| **Runtime** | **Node.js (TypeScript)** | Go, Elixir | While Elixir's Phoenix is great for websockets, the **Yjs** ecosystem in Node.js is the industry standard for modern collaborative tools (used by Jupyter, Notion-like clones). |
| **Communication** | **WebSockets (ws)** | SSE, HTTP Long Polling | Real-time editing requires low-latency bidirectional communication. WebSockets are the most efficient for this. |
| **Primary Database** | **PostgreSQL** | MongoDB | Postgres provides ACID compliance and excellent support for JSONB and binary data (needed for CRDT state vectors). |
| **Pub/Sub & Cache** | **Redis** | Nats, RabbitMQ | Redis is essential for horizontal scaling. It allows multiple server instances to sync document updates between users connected to different nodes. |

---

### System Architecture

The backend will follow a **state-update architecture**:
1. Users connect via WebSocket.
2. The server loads the "Document" (a Yjs Doc) from PostgreSQL.
3. When a user types, they send a binary "Update" (delta).
4. The server applies the update to its local model and broadcasts it to other users in the same room.
5. Periodically, the server persists a "Snapshot" to the DB to prevent the update log from growing indefinitely.

